    "explanation": "Wage differentials arise from differences in labour demand (MRPL) and supply. Demand-side: higher productivity, product prices, or capital per worker increase MRPL and wages. Supply-side: scarce skills, unpleasant conditions, or high training costs command higher wages. Non-monetary advantages (job security, pleasant environment, flexible hours) can explain lower wages — workers accept less pay for better non-wage benefits. Labour is a derived demand: demand depends on the demand for the goods labour produces. MRPL = MPP × MR under imperfect competition. Trade unions raise wages through collective bargaining. In monopsony, the employer pays below MRPL; a minimum wage can increase both wages AND employment. Therefore, C is the correct answer: \"C\"."
